# AI Agents to Automate Science by James Zhou

1. Virtual Lab 2. Paper2Agent 3. Agents4Science

## Virtual Lab
Interdisciplinary AI scientists that work with human scientists on challenging, open-ended
research

Agent Creation (ex. GPT-4o as the base model)
Team meeting (agents can have group meetings or 1 on 1 meetings for subtasks)
Individual meeting (tools in sandbox environment)


Principal Investigator (PI), Immunologist, Machine Learning Specialist,
Scientific Critic
All group members discuss 

Antibodies are commonly used as binders under many pharma and biotech companies.
Nanobodies only found in a few animals like camels. (cousins of antibodies)

Virtual Lab has increased efficiency due to having parallel meetings.
Agents can discuss 5x in paralled. PI takes transcipt of all meetings for summary.

Computational Biologist, Scientific Critic, Principal Investigator
Computational Biologist (28.1%): Does most of talking -> come up with plan for designing nanobodies
Scientific Critic (26.2%):
Principal Investigator(20.9%):
Machine Learning Specialist(17.7%): Do all coding for other agents, implements algorithms in Python or other languages 
Immunologist(5.9%): 
Human Researcher(1.3%): Don't talk too much; provide high-level guidance (ex. create binders, money constraints)


## Virtual Lab School of self-improving AI scientist
1.Choose Topics for Agents
2.Self Generate Queries
3.Search PMC & Select Papers

Go to PubMed, download article, read articles, SFT to update model parameters, 
perform next-token prediction, testing mechanism ...,
Then teacher agents generate quizzes to see how student agents perform. 

Start with o1 for an agent. Agents become more specialized through task progression.

### Ex. Virtual Lab designs nanobodies for recent COVID Variants
Agents pass 3d structure from AlphaFold into Rosetta (physics model)

Agents are able to rapidly reduce design space in to 92 nanobody candidates for binders.

